05517nam a22011295i 9780520931015DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20062006cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209310157 a10.1525/97805209310152doi  a(DE-B1597)519546  a(OCoLC)712793678  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBT741.3 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a248.22231 aHarvey, Susan Ashbrook, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScenting Salvation :bAncient Christianity and the Olfactory Imagination /cSusan Ashbrook Harvey. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (442 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTransformation of the Classical Heritage ;v4200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Olfactory Context: Smelling the Early Christian World -- t2. The Christian Body: Ritually Fashioned Experience -- t3. Olfaction and Christian Knowing -- t4. Redeeming Scents: Ascetic Models -- t5. Sanctity and Stench -- t6. Resurrection, Sensation, and Knowledge -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex of Biblical Citations -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book explores the role of bodily, sensory experience in early Christianity (first – seventh centuries AD) by focusing on the importance of smell in ancient Mediterranean culture. Following its legalization in the fourth century Roman Empire, Christianity cultivated a dramatically flourishing devotional piety, in which the bodily senses were utilized as crucial instruments of human-divine interaction. Rich olfactory practices developed as part of this shift, with lavish uses of incense, holy oils, and other sacred scents. At the same time, Christians showed profound interest in what smells could mean. How could the experience of smell be construed in revelatory terms? What specifically could it convey? How and what could be known through smell? Scenting Salvation argues that ancient Christians used olfactory experience for purposes of a distinctive religious epistemology: formulating knowledge of the divine in order to yield, in turn, a particular human identity. Using a wide array of Pagan, Jewish, and Christian sources, Susan Ashbrook Harvey examines the ancient understanding of smell through religious rituals, liturgical practices, mystagogical commentaries, literary imagery, homiletic conventions; scientific, medical, and cosmological models; ascetic disciplines, theological discourse, and eschatological expectations. In the process, she argues for a richer appreciation of ancient notions of embodiment, and of the roles the body might serve in religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aOdors. 0aSacrifice. 0aSenses and sensationxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aSmellxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistory. 0aSmell. 0aWorship. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aaffect theory.  aasceticism.  abodily senses.  abody.  aceremony.  achristianity.  achurch history.  acosmology.  adevotionals.  adivine order.  adivinity.  adoctrine.  aearly christianity.  aembodiment.  aeschatology.  ahistory.  aholy oils.  ahomily.  aincense.  aliturgy.  amediterranean culture.  amediterranean.  amystagogy.  anonfiction.  aolfactory.  apiety.  areligion and science.  areligious practice.  areligious studies.  arevelation.  arite.  aritual.  asacred scents.  asacred.  ascents.  asensation.  asense of smell.  asensibilia.  asensory experience.  asmell.  aspirituality.  atheology.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California